This article discusses an executive order issued by President Donald Trump on August 8, 2020. The order aims to prevent residential evictions and foreclosures resulting from financial hardships caused by the COVID-19 pandemic. The order acknowledges that the pandemic poses a significant threat to Americans' health and highlights the challenges faced by homeless shelters in preventing the spread of the virus. It also emphasizes the disproportionate impact of evictions on minority communities. The order directs various government agencies, including the Department of Health and Human Services, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the Department of the Treasury, and the Department of Housing and Urban Development, to take necessary measures to minimize evictions and foreclosures and provide temporary financial assistance to those struggling to meet their rental or mortgage obligations. The order emphasizes that it is the policy of the United States to minimize evictions and foreclosures during the ongoing COVID-19 national emergency.